tool.name: Ensemble_Model

param.name: in_ensemble_layers
param.expression: NetCDF File {NetCDF Variable} {Layer Type} {A} {BC} {D};NetCDF File {NetCDF Variable} {Layer Type} {A} {BC} {D}...
param.dialogReference:
The input evidence NetCDF files that will be combined using Dempster-Shafer Belief modelling. For each input, users must select:

- NetCDF Variable: a single variable from the input NetCDF representing the evidence layer.

- Layer Type: whether the evidence layer is belief or disbelief. Belief layers are those where higher values indicate high user belief that the target vegetation is present, whereas higher values in disbelief layers indicate high levels of user certainy that the target does not exist. At least one of both belief and disbelief layers are required to perform Dempster-Shafer.

- A: the fuzzy sigmoidal inflection point on the left side of the bell curve (typically the lowest dataset value for belief, highest for disbelief). This value (and any value under it) will be set to zero during sigmoidal rescaling.

- BC: the fuzzy sigmoidal mid-point inflection point of the bell curve. Leave as N/A if you want to rescale only to minimum (A) and maximum (D), or vice versa for disbelief.

- D: the fuzzy sigmoidal inflection point on the right side of the bell curve (typically the highest dataset value for belief, lowest for disbelief). This value (and any value under it) will be set to one during sigmoidal rescaling.

param.name: out_ensemble_nc_path
param.dialogReference: The folder location and filename of the output NetCDF file containing Demspter-Shafer ensemble modelling data.

param.name: in_resample_to
param.dialogReference: Whether to resample all input NetCDF evidence layers to the lowest detected resolution or the highest amongst all evidence layers. All evidence layers will be clipped and resampled to match the detected layer.

param.name: in_add_result_to_map
param.dialogReference: Whether to visualise the results to the currently active map once modelling is complete or not.

tool.summary:
Perform Dempster-Shafer belief modelling. This module intends to take two or more NetCDF file inputs, where each layer is designated as either belief or disbelief. For belief inputs, higher values represent areas where the user expects to find their target vegetation. In contrast, disbelief layers should hold higher values where the user expects not find the target vegetation. The benefit of this method is that not only can multiple evidence layers be combined statistically, but Dempster-Shafer outputs include additional maps showing areas of model plausibility and uncertainty (i.e., under-sampled areas of the landscape that might need attention).

See citation: https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/dempster-shafer-theory.
